Richard Oswald's German film “Anders als die Andern” (“Different from the Others”), the world’s first feature film with explicit and sympathetic gay characters, is pivotal in the history of queer cinema. Released in 1919, it is one of the oldest surviving movies with a gay protagonist. The film was made post World War I, a rare period, when German film censorship was considered more relaxed. The film centres around a violinist who takes his life after getting blackmailed for his sexuality and ends with an appeal for gay tolerance by German gay rights activist Magnus Hirschfeld. Despite being over a 100 years old, the film holds relevance even today. 
#historyofcinema #pridemonth #loveislove

Source: UCLA Film & Television Archive on YouTube.
